# Go: compile-time interface satisfaction

When concrete type must implement interface (especially cross-package contract like `relay.Metrics`), add package-level blank-identifier assignment.
Compiler then enforces contract at build time. Signature drift fails fast.

## Pattern

Pointer receiver (common for mutable structs):

Use `(*T)(nil)`. No allocation. Compile-time only.

```go
// ASSERT: BridgeMetrics implements relay.Metrics
var _ relay.Metrics = (*BridgeMetrics)(nil)
```

Value receiver (only when value methods satisfy interface):

```go
// ASSERT: MyReader implements io.Reader
var _ io.Reader = MyReader{}
```

## Where to put it

- Put right above concrete type, or right below type block, in implementing package.
- Prefer one-line comment like `// ASSERT: <Type> implements <pkg.Interface>`.

## When to add or skip

- Add for public contracts (DI, plugin, cross-package API) where mismatch would surface late.
- Optional for tiny same-package interfaces already enforced by call sites, still useful if interface may grow.

## Related conventions in this repo

- In this repo, interfaces often defined at use site, implementations elsewhere. Assertion is cheap compile-time link between them.
